76561198045208825,Not Recommended,223510,28116470,"Posted: 1 December, 2016",all,Shatiz,"Summary:Miasmata is not really a bad game, it has potential, but it is not one I would recommend anyone to play. It feels unfinished, like it is lacking some essential key aspects for making it a really good experience. The graphics, the story and the gameplay are all quite lacklustre. There are no puzzles, no character interactions and essentially no combat.Review:I finished the game, but I cannot say why, other than pure stubbornness.  The graphics are not too bad, but not exactly gorgeous (and view distance is pretty awful), which is a problem. The game consists almost exclusively of exploration, but there really isn't that much to explore. Sure, the island is big, but you don't really get those ""wow, what an awesome place"" experiences. You see an interesting looking ruin in the distance and you run there... and there is nothing to see. That's the experience you will have all the time, in between running through relatively bland vegetation.Similarly, the story is okay, with notes scattered around to give some idea of both who the people on the island were and the place they were coming from. But as you don't meet any people and the main character never speaks, there is a very empty feeling. I did not find all the notes, but the ones I did offered a pretty lacklustre story that evoked more ""Oh... okay then"" rather than ""Wow, I wanna find all the notes and figure out what is going on."". I found myself looking for the notes mostly to find maps of the area and directions to the cure ingredients. And its good that they are there, but it doesn't make them very interesting. Getting the ingredients also doesn't require any special ability or thought-process. It's all spelled out in the notes, you just have to walk to the right place. There are no puzzles in the game.So what about the gameplay? Well, there is very little. The game is actually very easy, I only died once... because the creature hit me through a wall. And it really is THE creature, because there is only one enemy type in the entire game. The only other enemy is the controls. You have to be careful of how you run as you are very likely to fall over, even at small inclinations. And you slide like you're wearing rollerskates. And falling will give you fever so you must make medicine. But that only serves to slow you down. If you don't run too fast and you avoid the creature (which is not very hard) you will be fine. And once you realise that, the tension kinda disappears. There is nothing to fear on this island but boredom.So overall, I did not hate my time with Miasmata, but the only really memorable part was the frustration from the controls. I would not play it again and I would not recommend it to anyone else."
