76561198075673573,Recommended,223510,25067888,"Posted: 21 August, 2016",all,wrygrass,"I rate the game Miasmata 3.5/5. Pretty good..if you have a lot of patience and enjoy games which feature fairly quiet, peaceful natural surroundings.This, being the second game in which I've played as a person who is ill (The first being Far Cry 2) is a slow-paced, generally peaceful, first person perspective survival game wherein you must maneuver your weakened, occasionally feverish character around a rugged series of tropical and subtropical islands to find various fungi and flowers and then bring them back to various scattered laboratories to find out what properties they have in an ongoing attempt to get yourself cured. If you walk too fast or (unlike in Skyrim) walk down a hill which is too steep you may end up running and then falling which will decrease your health, may cause your fever to worsen (because you have over-exerted yourself I guess) and you will drop everything you are carrying and may not be able to easily find it again. Also, in this game your character can get exhausted, dehydrated and, if you make him swim for too long, may even drown. Going for a long time without sleep will also weaken your health. Standing around in the beautifully rendered tropical rain however has no effect on your health whatsoever. You never seem to have to eat anything though if you did have to, the game probably would have taken forever to finish.This game is fairly long and requires great patience as simply making your character walk down a hill without falling down can be a challenge in itself. To put it another way, trying to get around in this game is probably a lot like being really old (except you can move more quickly than the elderly). If that wasn't enough of a challenge already, there are carnivorous creatures (they aren't creepy though as they look a lot like panthers with horns glued onto their heads and odd, hand-like feet) on the island which occasionally show up to hunt you. I don't think the creature was actually one but maybe several solitary creatures which live on the island (like mountain lions or something). But take heart, as you find cures for yourself your condition improves and with it, your ability to more easily move around the islands.The game's plot does have some loose threads. You can find old journal entries which suggest that one of the island's inhabitants went crazy and, given the way the corpses around the island apparently died (with a knife stuck into each them). However this murderer never materializes. I guess he ran off into the jungle and killed himself...or maybe he somehow was transformed one of the cat-creatures which occasionally stalks you to the loud sound of your beating heartbeat. There are also two distinct types of ruins in the island setting of this game but nothing can be found out about either group who built the ruins. Indeed, the ruins exist primarily to serve as mere landmarks to help mapping the islands easier. This game often hints at a more complex and detailed plot the sum-total explanation of which is frustratingly not to be found anywhere in this game. Still this game in all its interest and unusual gameplay and beauty is amazing for when we consider it appears to have been put together by just two people (brothers I think) over the course of what I heard was four years.Now that you know the gist of what Miasmata is, it's time to break down what the pros and cons of this game are.Good things about this game:+This game is often remarkably beautiful, particularly if you enjoy the natural beauties which this world has to offer. The tropical and sub-tropical island setting has lots of wonderful sunsets, trees and nifty rays of light filtering through the trees. The colors are vibrant and the reflections off of water are pretty also. The rain effect was particularly well done and better by far than the awful rain effect in the 2010 version of Need For Speed: Hot Pursuit. The rain in Miasmata was wonderful and other game developers should take a look at how the rain was done here. That said, the overall graphical detail of this game is rather mediocre.+This game relies heavily on the natural sounds of the world with sparse and almost entirely instrumental music playing only very rarely. The sounds are done very well except in one situation.+Overall this game was rewarding and interesting through to the end. A true and beautiful work of art. While not the most moving or emotional game ever it was definitely fun and the sense of mystery never went away (because unfortunately, many things were never fully explained). By the time I was done with the game I was ready for it to be over and so it lasted just the right length of time for me to feel fulfilled and refreshed by this game's unusual first person perspective survival concept. This game was a true adventure.Mediocre things about this game:+/-The graphics do tend to be simple. Your limbs are fairly blocky. Indeed, most objects tend to be fairly blocky when viewed up-close. The clouds are often curiously tinged with brown and when combined with the intermittent atmospheric haze and the fact that the fog in this game looks a lot more like smoke it accidentally feels as though the islands are supposed to be on fire somehow. The islands you are wandering around in are not supposed to be on fire but it often sure does look as though they must be.+/-The carnivorous creatures can, from some angles, almost look cute due to their cat-like appearance. You are clearly supposed to find them terrifying but they aren't. They just seem more like some sort of weirdly mutated, previously unknown species of jungle cat which sees you as potential prey. At the same time though, this lends an added air of realism to the environment.+/- Finding the plants you need to concoct a cure is very difficult and made even more difficult by the presence of the creature hunting you whenever you are near a plant that you absolutely need to grab.+/-You can only save your game at certain geographic locations but these locations are so numerous that saving my game was never much of a problem.Bad things about this game:-The controls are definitely difficult. It often feels, especially early on that your character must be just learning how to use roller skates which have somehow become permanently attached to his feet. This roller skate feeling never really left either but as I progressed through the game I found myself learning how to handle the character better, even putting him into controlled slides occasionally to get down slopes more quickly. Some of the other controls (picking stuff up with your right hand without dropping stuff in your left hand for example) were also a bit clunky.-The one time when the sound is not good is when a carnivorous creature is hunting you and your heartbeat sounds WAY TOO LOUDLY in your ears. This sound didn't increase my sense of tension. It merely increased my sense of irritation. I often wanted to avoid the creatures not so much because they were scary but because i didn't want the loud heartbeat sound to intrude on the quiet ambience of the game more than it had to.-Once you have a carnivorous cat creature's attention it is VERY HARD to hide and get it to go elsewhere. Sometimes I would hide and it would just wait forever for me to come out even though it couldn't see me.-I wish this game had more scary moments or had capitalized more on the numerous scary moments it was sort of trying to have. I wonder what this game would have been had it been somehow done with the far more beautiful game engine used in Far Cry 3 somehow. The graphics often seemed a bit dated. Still, Far Cry 3 was made by a team of people which formed a list longer than my arms and Miasmata is an amazing achievement for what seems to have been just 2 people."
