76561197970437631,Recommended,223510,8570483,"Posted: 5 January, 2014",all,nikjson,"Maismata - a game reviewExperienceThis, I feel, is the most important part and the best reason for playing this game. The looks, your movements, the sounds, the story and the mechanics all work together to make this an interesting and immersive experience. You feel that the character, you, isn't doing well, that you're often exhausted and have to fight both the exotic environment as well as your illness. You huff and puff at any exertion, thirst and untreated fevers impair your vision and coordination, falls will often disorient you and even finding out just where you are is something of a chore. Day-to-day survival is work here, giving you a sense of vulnerability, compounded by the fear of the Creature.I'll give each of these a closer look below.LooksThis is a very good-looking game, most of the time. There are a few graphic oddnesses, like the arms and hands that, while important and immersive can't help looking a little awkward at times. Texture pop-in and the sometimes very 'grainy' water are easily forgivable sins, seeing that most everything else works very well. Special mention should be made of the day and night cycle. Not only do dawns and sunsets look fantastic, as do the rays of sunlight filtered through the trees, they also actually work. Looking toward a brighter light, like the sun or a torch, will make dark areas even darker and more difficult to navigate. Nights are very dark indeed, there being nothing more than the moon and stars to light your way. Your lighter is a decent emergency light and burning twigs or a torch will properly light up your immediate area, helping you find your way to some sort of shelter.MovementI suspect that many will find moving around in this game to be an awkward business, much unlike the fluid movements in other First Person games. Moving forwards is generally fine but try any looking-left-while-strafing-right to look around while moving or a very quick turn and you're in for a surprise. It would seem that Robert can't run sideways as fast as he can run forwards. This shouldn't be the shock it is, since most people can't. You also have momentum to contend with - running downhill can be a very bad idea and may easily run you right over a ledge into a nasty fall. Climbing hills is a slow to laborious process which is further influenced by your current state. Thirst and fever will make you weaker and slower, making progress more difficult.If all this sounds awkward and off-putting, you can rest assured that there are good and design-conscious reasons behind every seeming impediment.SoundThe soundscape of Miasmata is fairly minimal but well implemented. There are near-constant ambient noises, such as wind, rustles, trickling or rushing water, bird-calls, crashing waves or rain, but next to no score. There's music in the game, to be sure, but it's held back to mark certain locations or the odd special moment.  Your footfalls have their own sounds, in keeping with whatever surface you're on, which is a nice touch. Loose rocks and crackling twigs could have a few more samples though, being a bit repetetive.MechanicsA brief look at some of the different ways things are done in the game.Medicinesare ""synthesized"" in the labs around the Island, using one or two plants for each new type. Each plant first has to be found and examined. How to do this is clearly explained in the first few notes you find and works well. The process does get repetetive but the animations can be interrupted. A few more different animations would be nice to have. Notes scattered around the island will tell you where to look for crucial elements and thus give you a good incentive to travel all over the place.Cartographyis a large and important feature in the game. You have precious little idea of where you are, most of the time, since you have to 'draw' the map on your own. This is accomplished by triangulating your current position, using your compass and known landmarks. Distant and unknown landmarks can be triangulated by moving between two known positions and marking them on the map. Much like in real life. Well implemented, with a chance of a minor 'exploit' as a handy shortcut.Timedoes flow here, as shown by your watch and the well made day/night-cycle. This gives you a sense of urgency, since being caught out after dark has the very real consequense of easily losing your way to that shelter and bed. Unfortunately, the sense of urgency is diminished by the fact that you don't see a definite progression of your illness, that you can stay alive on water and medicine indefinitely.The Creatureis a somewhat mysterious and certainly threatening presence on the island. It can turn up at nearly any time and will likely send chills down your spine as you hear the sudden thump of your own heartbeat, reminding you of your precarious situation. There are techniques and medicinal boosts that can help you avoid being found, which is a good thing, seeing as you're in no shape to fight this beast. Well done, overall, but it does occasionally get stuck in a loop, which can be annoying.StoryI intentionally left this for last, since it's in the manual and of litte importance. When starting the game, you're placed in the shoes of Robert Hughes, a plague-stricken scientist, stranded on an unknown island, in search of a cure. Precisely why a name is mentioned is something of a mystery, since the who of you is of utter insignificance to anything that happens in the game. (Here the developers missed a chance to involve female players a little more.) The more imortant words are 'stranded', made evident by your bloody hands and the wrecked boat beside you and 'plague-stricken', as you'll notice shortly.Fever, thirst, brutally murdered scientists, mysterious messages, baffling notes, helpful discoveries, rain, darkness, swamps, glorious sunsets, coluorful fungi and more plants than you can shake a burning twig at will help and hinder and baffle you on your journey.Your goal, ultimately, is to find the cure and escape this island. The cure is to be found among the rich flora of the island, which you will research, annotate and cook up various medicines from. Some will just be a temporary stay of your recurring fevers and some will give you more lasting effects. To help your progress, you'll find the notes of the expedition scattered around in their huts and tents.Escaping the island, alive, will not be easy.There are some missed opportunities for exposition and deepening the story, such as conspiracies or cover-ups that are just hinted at, the obvious mystery of the murders which could be better developed and the odd and disconcerting Creature.RecommendationAll in all, I found this to be a very rewarding exerience. I thoroughly enjoyed the lush environments of the island, the often beautiful vistas opening up in front of me as I clear the crest of a hill, the deep dark of the nights and the heart-pounding fear of being found by the Creature. I even liked the work of mapping my progress around the island, since it added both realism and a feeling of accomplishment set against the helplessness of being lost.Kudos and a hearty 'Well done!' to the brothers of IonFX."
76561198042757315,Recommended,223510,20585282,"Posted: 17 January, 2016",all,SamuraiCupcake,"I got a good 12 hours of exploration and adventure!Pros :-A truly beautiful game. Worth it just to get lost in it.-Once you get used to movement, it actually becomes an extra challenge just to move up and down slopes. Its quite fun!-I would get giddy with excitement whenever I'd discover a new plant and would hurry back to the lab to check it out!-Tons of different drugs to craft and use-The creature won't appear often, but when the character's heart starts pumping, yours will too!-The creature acts in a believable way! There are several different ways to deal with it... some ending with your death.-After trekking in the wilderness, you truly get a feeling of satisfaction when you discover an outpost.-You are completely free to explore at your leasure in any direction. The island is also massive!-The cartography system is awesome. Later in the game I had a lot of fun mapping out the entire island.-When night falls it gets very dark... which is very scary. Add to it the monster on the prowl and you have a bit of horror.Cons-Character is a bit too prone to falling and tripping down slight hills. It gets annoying/frustrating.-Some areas won't be of much use later on -  more quantity over quality (vast areas with just trees, useless ruins, etc)-Ruins are a bit of a dissapointment : there are no secrets nor lore to it. Who built them? You won't know.-There is a bit of a tease with ''Psychotic episodes'' and ''hallucinations'' being mentioned in a paper, but it doesn't happen. If you let the fever worsen you just die.-Survival is unrealistically easy - no need to hunt nor eat, and resting in a shoddy cot in a tent will cure you of heavy fever. Taking pills also instantly makes you better. I kinda wish it worked like that IRL.-The ending is pretty sad and disappointing. Didn't feel like my efforts payed off.All in all, I'd say the pro far outweigh the cons. It is very impressive that two guys made this game from scratch!If you like exploration, discovery, ambiance, science with only a little bit of scare, then you will really enjoy this one.Wholeheartedly recommend."
,Recommended,223510,811592,"Posted: 3 February, 2013",all,mark | dj.,"Miasmata is a great idea with a somewhat flawed execution.You're a scientist on an island looking for a cure. To find this cure you have to find plants and create potions, while triangulating landmarks to create your own map of the island.The island is huge and you're free to go wherever you want, as long as you can keep yourself alive. You have to be careful that you don't dehydrate, drown, get killed by a creature (I haven't encountered it myself yet) or that you take your medicine in time.The game is played from a first person perspective, which actually works quite alright, but walking and running (and especially stopping/slowing down) can be awkward and clumsy. It tries to be realistic by slowing down your character when climbing up the hills or speeding up when you're heading downwards. Most of the times it seems random and I've lost count of how many times I've fallen.You're also allowed to carry a maximum of 3 different plants at the same time, and you can't carry more than one of the same plant. So most of the times you have to make multiple trips. However, there are cabins scattered across the island. These cabins allow you to transfer your plants between any of them, which helps, but limiting the amount of plants you can carry is still a bit frustrating. On the other hand, it does create a certain tension so I guess there's something to be said for it. Especially traveling when it's dark is not recommended, because it can get pitchblack without any torches. And then there's this creature I keep hearing about...So, I'm having some mixed emotions here. I guess I shall be taking my journal and compass, and enter the world once more to see if my opinion changes for the better... or for the worse.[Rating: 73/100]"
