76561198012852661,Recommended,223510,21418806,"Posted: 23 February, 2016",all,Johnny Waffles,"This game was amazing; it was everything I expected it to be. It's a pretty mellow slow paced exploration game that requires patience. The island is beautiful and the weather was fantastic. The story and concept are great especially the cartography. The creature was a little scary, a little annoying, but played its part very well. I didn’t even mind the bumbling controls once I got used to them, in fact they added to the experience.I managed to play for 32 hours across 1 full playthrough, 1 speed run (achievements), and 1 playthrough for remaining achievements.I'm a little disappointed the devs abandoned the game leaving behind some achievement bugs. Nothing game breaking unless you consider getting all the achievements important like I do.Huge shout out toDarkStarSwordfor his excellent work on theUnofficial Community PatchandMiaschievbug fixer. I couldn't have completed the game without his work.Once the game is done, there is no replay value which saddens me a lot. I want to play again but the game is exactly the same every time. I wish there was a ""random"" playthrough where the important flowers changed requiring you to analyze them each time to figure out their use. The flowers could also randomize locations and the maps and notes would not be present since you already know the story.10/10 Would play again if I could."
76561198334465911,Recommended,223510,28092013,"Posted: 29 November, 2016",all,Mega Bunny,"This is my ultimate sleeper game. You wake up on a mysterious island with blood on your hands. At first, it's an ambulation simulator.  Walk around, pick flowers and orientate yourself to your surroundings. Just like your gran on a day-trip to a botanic garden,except your gran isn't being chased by an ethereal demon, trying to escape from a lost island, and synthesising drugs to survive.As your character progresses, they pick up the basics of ethno-botany, cartography and organic chemistry. You develop a deep appreciation of regular hydration and the plot gets weirder and weirder by the minute. Armed only with a feeble throwing arm, a selection of rotting fruit and the occasional burning twig, you uncover the mystery behind your disease.I couldn't let the story go. I dug deeper and deeper. I got to the ending and thought this game is a worthy successor to the literary novel. Hyperbole aside, this game is intriguing, deeply satisfying and introduced me to a narrative driven experience that is a well-crafted alternative to the alpha-wave twitch. Miasmata has a highly  enjoyable discovery/survival game mechanic with an excellent soundscape. Your own heartbeat never sounded so terrifying.It still astounds me  that it was made by only two people. It needs a sequel."
