76561197969417125,Recommended,223510,353364,"Posted: 5 March, 2013",all,G00N3R,"In Miasmata, the player explores an island in search of plants, to craft a cure for a disease. The game is almost entirely non combat, which may put off some gamers. You will be attacked by a creature at various times, but its best to just run away and hide. You can also be injured by falling down hills, and will die if you don't heal fast enough. Other threats include thirst, sleep deprivation and drowning. Crafting plants can restore health and provide buffs. I loved how much freedom the player is given. Miasmata is a lesson for AAA developers about how to create an open world without waypoint markers, and still guide the player to quest locations in an intelligent way. There are lots of clues to find such as maps and journal fragments, which point you in the right direction. If you're willing to overlook some minor flaws such as graphical glitches and menu presentation, this is a really nice, intelligent game, and easily worth the indie game purchase price."
76561198025994109,Recommended,223510,20878994,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,Collimation,"While you can win this game within 5 minutes, it will probably take you about 24 hours to play.  It is cheeky like that.  If you like orienteering around an island trying to find useful stuff to help you survive and mixing drugs and going for the occasional sliding tumble to yuor death through foliage while being chased by Cat-thulhu (or was it Tabbythogua?) this game might be for you.  It is not a typical game, in that you lack the tools necessary to kill the critter, but you are on the island to save your civilization from a terrible plague, and if you are clever, you will.  I loved scurrying through the underbrush trying to find the proper vantage points to triangulate distances and map the world, it was an odd and enjoyable mechanic that I became kinda OCD about doing over and over again.  Finishing this game was strangely satisfying and I liked it, but I just know it will not be everyone's ""cup of tea""."
,Recommended,223510,31498034,Posted: 1 May,all,Bearji™,"I didn't enjoy this game at first. I put it down and finally came back to it years later. Again I had issues coming to terms with elements of the game.  The movement felts sluggish. The cartography system felt obtuse. But these elements serve a purpose that makes Miasmata a very positive experience on the whole.  The movement system is one you learn to use. It only feels sluggish in that any other movement system is very forgiving, whereas Miasmata's can be punishing.  As a sick man in an unwelcoming landscape, rather than contending with terrorists or zombies, your struggle is you against the land.  A misstep can mean doom if you're scaling a steep hill to get a better vantage point on your surrondings.  Likewise, carelessly skirting a cliff or running down uneven terrain can send you painfully tumbling.  However, once you learn how to move, it becomes second nature and you find yourself discovering safe pathways through the rough wilderness.  The cartography system, similarly, does not hold your hand and guide you through the game.  Instead it is a tool that you use to guide yourself using landmarks.  The game rewards you generously for taking the initiative to explore by planning your trip around keeping known landmarks in sight and discovering new ones to expand your records of the island.Miasmata is a very refreshing game if you're tired of hand-holding open world games and want an experience of exploration unrivaled by anything in recent memory."
,Recommended,223510,19706047,"Posted: 14 December, 2015",all,Keiichigo,"This is a wonderfully designed game.I love the work they've put in it and the whole exploration aspect of it of trying to find a cure and being exiled on an island.The feeling of helplessness is really present. However, they are still a few bugs that needs to be addressed/fixed before they role this out into the public. I don't know why steam only logged me for 0.2 hours on this game when I clearly spent 2 hours or more exploring everything, but here's my take on some of the negative thinks I found in the game.1.) Often times, my character would clip through rocky surfaces, house walls, trees and even fall under the map. This needs to be fixed.2.) Sometimes when you die, the character's voice would get stuck in a loop until you restart, load or exit the game.3.) Often times I would die for no reason, such as walking knee-high on water or clipping houses and structures.Apart from that, this game has been very wonderful. While I do believe and feel that this game still feels like it's in early access and should be polished up more, I will not deny that this game offers replayability and numerous content for players to enjoy. I hope the developers take the time to address these issues with an update in the future.8/10 - My honest review."
