,Recommended,223510,30255878,Posted: 28 February,all,Andi,"Miasmata is an open world, survival, adventure game where you must craft medicines to cure a disease that is slowing killing you.  There are other medicines that you can create to help you on your journey but beware, for the interior of the island lurks a creature that is hell bent on killing you before the plague does.  Unfortunately, that's where many of the plants grow that can aid your condition.Pros:- Highly detailed world- Passage of time- The island is very diverse in it's topography- Mapping the island is fun (at lease for me it was)- Various plants, many with medicinal properties- Many notes and pictures to find that will give you clues to plant locations- You get to play scientist- There is no place on the island where you can't go- Numerous unique buildings, ruins, tents, dot the landscape, several with notes so you want to visit them allCons:- The game is not well optimized- It is very VERY easy to get lost if you leave the path and you will leave the path... many times- The creature seems to show up at the most inconvenient times (but then again, it's more of a pet peeve then a con)Besides fashioning medicines, one of the most entertaining activities for me was mapping the island.  I've always had a interest in cartography.  If you want to map the entire island, you have to be clever on where you stand and find two known points of reference, especially when it comes to mapping the interior.At the time of this review, Miasmata was selling for $14.99.  Well worth it in my opinion."
,Recommended,223510,1126861,"Posted: 6 February, 2013",all,Lincoln Balloon,"Miasmata is a tough game to recommend.  It's not that the game is particularly bad or anything (I think it's a great experience honestly), but it's one of those games that is so unique that it will most likely polarize people.Miasmata is a game of survival and exploration.  You wake up on the shores of an uncharted island stricken with a plague.  Your primary goal is to cure it, and you do this by collecting plants, researching them, and discovering their properties.  This is what you'll spend most of the game doing, aside from dealing with the occasional run in with the creature that roams the isle.  The game is highly immersive.  It pulls you in with a strong sense of place.The only major issues with this game comes from the technical side.  There are lots of graphical glitches here and there (the pop in is particularly bad at some points), and the framerate occasionally dips (at least on my laptop it did).  Considering the game was designed entirely by two brothers, I can actually look past most of these issues.If you want a gaming experience like nothing you've played before, I would highly recommend this game.  If you are not the patient type, I would caution you on this one.  This is definitely a game that rewards patient exploration, and if that's your thing, then you are in for a treat."
