76561197968305227,Not Recommended,223510,34724695,Posted: 3 September,all,ChaosEngine,"This was the second indie game I ever got really interested in, (after Sangfroid). It's a real shame it took me so long to get to it, because now that I have, I am not impressed.Visuals are ok, and I'm not usually picky about them. Tension was non-existant during the first hour or so... the monster they hype up in the trailers doesn't even make a scripted appearance to help build said tension. It might've been out there, it might not, but after an hour of play I would have expected something after how much time is spent hyping it up in the trailer.Game details are obtuse... couldn't figure out the triangulation mechanics, but that's also fine. Things don't always need to be spelled out to you and if you're willing to spend hours with a product you can definitely learn. All in all, the setup was one for a game that could have been savoured, rather than rushing to get to the good bits.However, I'm not savouring anything because of the SECOND. WORST. FIRST. PERSON. CONTROLS. EVER. The only controls that I've experienced that are worse are from Datura for PS4.Movement is arduous at best, ridiculously floaty at worst. Running is the only way to get anywhere in decent time, but watch out that you don't go down hill for any reason, because you will trip, you will fall, and then you're stuck hiking back to a bed to sleep off the resulting fever... yes, a fever from falling. Climbing up anywhere is equally painful, where a slope you would have no problem scaling in real life is impossible, and you keep sliding down. Yes, you could argue this was done for realism, but there's a fine line between realism and unfun.Hard pass, if you want something similar go play the Forest, Minecraft, Don't Starve, or 7 Days to Die. They all have survival elements, crafting, roughly equivalent graphics, and you're being hunted by enemies that actually show up in the first hour, all without making you want to grind your teeth to dust as you try to move through the world."
