76561197992404497,Not Recommended,223510,21359160,"Posted: 21 February, 2016",all,Arcanix,"This is one of those unpolished ""games"" that takes minimalism - and itself - too seriously. Ultimately, it's the little things that make this game unenjoyable.1. ""What the heck am I seeing?""When you shave off so much of the UI as to be non-existant, you defeat the purpose. There is almost no in-game text to help discern what you are looking at. I am not a botanist, so don't expect me to instantly categorize and identify each plant the game presents. Since textures are recycled so much, it is impossible to discern or orient yourself (see gripe #3).2. ""What the heck am I hearing?""Put simply, the sound is atrocious. It lacks true ambience, and the music only comes up in the menu. Most annoying is the fact that the same bass effect is used for being preyed upon by predators AND the sound of your heart when you strain yourself, so after one too many encounters you cannot tell if your character is just paranoid or stupid.3. ""Where the heck am I?""Getting lost sucks. It isn't fun to try to figure out where you are. Coming back to the game later means having almost no idea where anything is anymore. You get a map, but you have to fill it in manually by way of triangulation... except that the surroundings are so thick that you cannot view almost any landmark - and no, you cannot look through the foliage. The fact that you are under pressure of a disease means meandering about aimlessly is not an option... which takes us to gripe number 4.4. You can only carry one of anything.I spent hours of game time harvesting ingredients and making multiple doses of key medicines, only to find later that I only had one dose in my inventory. The game never tells you that your giant pillbox can hold only a single dose of anything. I get easily fifty mints in an Altoid tin, so don't tell me this is even close to the realism they otherwise try to evoke.5. Immersion is great, until it becomes boring.Walking simulators have to strike a fine balance between distance and speed, and this game strikes out on this concept. After the third time getting exhausted for having to sprint, it gets annoying. The environments aren't so spectacular that I can enjoy these woods. Firewatch got it much better. Look, I get that the character is supposed to be some weakling geek, but asthma sucks enough in real life without needing to bring it into a game. What next, ""chemo sim 1995, where you get to watch your body rot!"" - no thanks.6. Slopes and momentum are not your friend.More to the point, you have all the control of a drunkard. Walking along a slight bank, only to have the angle shift juuuust enough so that the game decides you get to take a tumble downhill is just aggravating.7. Tools get lost with a sneeze, but plant samples? Deathgrip!The game tries so hard to be realistic but the fact that if you swim or fall then you are forced to drop weapons, yet your samples remain grasped firmly in hand is contradictory. Annoying design choices are blatant for being sophomorish.8. Food is unnecessary, apparently!Exertion, exhaustion, strain, thirst, carrying capacity... all of these are carefully tracked in the game. Survival should incorporate food/hunger. Maybe I never got that far in the game, but after 4 days in the game world, you would expect some grumblies in the tumblies. Rabbit is tasty!9. Critters. Critters everywhere, and more silent than ninjas!Add them to the ambience, or let us kill them for food. The fuzzy animals should make fine eats, but the varmints and vermin are purely atmospheric.10. Useless samples are uselessLiterally, why bother at all? I get it, some of them don't make medicines. However the fact that this botanist can't turn them into deterrents for predators is ludicrous. Since the UI is so minimal, there is literally no way to drop the useless stuff. Worst of all, using them in crafting wastes the useful materials - you have to figure that out, however, the hard way.11. You cannot escape the menuThis seems like a minor gripe, but it is like I said at the start that the little things add up. Having to click out of the menu that you can only access by way of the ESC key is just another example of how the developer fails to understand basic concepts of UX.TL;DR:This game is just bad. Play it if you enjoy role-playing a suffering, dying, asthmatic dweeb with zero survival skills and no preservation instinct."
