76561198045942581,Recommended,223510,5172892,"Posted: 14 April, 2013",all,Sgt.Puppy,"Miasmata is a First-Person Survival Game with a strong focus on discovery and exploration.You are a criminal (forgot the name, sorry about that), who gets banished on an island. You also are sick and have to find different plants and fungi to create a cure and then escape the island. But you are not alone. A creature follows you across the island and tries to kill you. Will you survive to find a cure ?Miasmata has the same combat mechanics as popular horror-games like Amnesia and Outlast. There are none. The only thing you can do during creature encounters is run and hide, which creates a tension and you sometimes almost go mental, because the creature is pretty deadly and hard to escape from. But honestly, I am a bit disappointed by the creatures AI and the spawning points. Sometimes you run away from the beast, just to encounter it a couple hundred meters further again, this time infront of you. Or one time it spawned on a small island at the beach and was unable to swim, so it could just look at it without any danger. I would not call such cases bugs, but they brake the illusion of a superior enemy and quickly show the mechanics behind it.Still, the fact, that creature encounters are quite rare at times and your hearth starts to beat, when the creature is near, builds tention and you got a good chance to escape.But 98 % there is gameplay without fleeing from the creature. In this time you have to find plants with which you can create different kinds of medicines. With those, you can cure injuries (which can kill you after some time), can boost your stamina, strench, perception and ultimately cure your illness, which makes you a pretty weak human being. Without any boosts of medicine, your swimming and sprintingrange are very limited and noticing your worst enemy is up to you. But collecting and finding plants to create medicine is necessary and ultimately the goal of the game.Finding very specific plants for specific cures can be very difficulte. The main problem besides surviving is orientation. You have to draw your own map through triangulation. You do this with markpoint, represented through statues, buildings, ruins, and pillars, which you find scattered over the map. Whenever you can see two such points, you draw your surroundings. This can be pretty difficulte and forgetting to draw your map can get you lost pretty quickly. The fact, that you do not see your position on the map without boosting your perception, makes it even more difficulte.From time to time, you find mappieces in huts, which sometimes show you the location on your map, sometimes just hint at it. Finding specific plants can be really annoying, but also rewarding, when you finally get your piece of the cure or another boost to run faster or longer.Graphicaly, the game is mediocre at best, aiming at a realistic graphic style. But honestly, it never bothered me, the landscape looks nice, little bunnies run away from you, butterflies and birds fly around, you hear the wind blowing. Everything is very athmospheric and the graphics fit. There are games out there with way better graphics, but look also way ugglier.Verdict: Miasmata is a very athmospheric survival game. It builds a feeling of loneliness, in a cheerfull world, while being hunted by a fearsome creature. The survival aspects could be done better and finding plants can be ridiculous and getting lost is daily business. But despite these flaws, Miasmata is a solid game, which deserves your playtime."
