,Recommended,223510,1909184,"Posted: 13 March, 2013",all,[V13]Dizazter,"Miasmata is an exploration, survival, horror game. (In that order of significance) If you enjoy getting lost in Minecraft and finding your way back to your known area, you'll enjoy this game. I'd say its a mix of Minecraft exploration (without dynamic environments or mining, but some crafting), the ""LOST"" like island mystery, and some Dear Esther visuals and minimal action gameplay.  It also has some Myst elements to it, without the awkward puzzles. There is a cartography element where you need to reference two familiar landmarks (statues etc) to locate yourself and surrounding on the map, and do this with a 3rd new landmark from two different locations to make the new landmark a familiar one. There is a threat on the island, but its hasnt been a big issue for me yet. But my big gripe is the physics of slopes, basically your character struggles to climb even a 5 degree slope, and you can easily fall. Basically it feels like you're wearing roller skates in the wilderness. Also, you have a sickness that constantly requires medicine, so going in water and falling, makes you get sick a lot faster. Good mechanic I guess to keep people from just swiming everywhere. There are also a lot of impassible terrain to get around. So if you're into exploration and mystery, this might be a game for you. But not so much there on the action end, but there are some good survival elements, which can be intense, as you race to make more medicine to survive. One bummer is you only get 1 save slot per game. But all round its something different and fun for those into exploration."
,Recommended,223510,3641365,"Posted: 17 March, 2013",all,Vanyalosswen,"Back when Myst first came out, there was a Fox Trot cartoon in which Jason hacked up a version of Myst that was exactly the same as the original, except that velociraptors were chasing the player. That's a pretty good description of Miasmata.Exploration is the driving mechanic of the game, and in this respect, the island of Eden is a paradise. Every part of the island is unique, with hills, rivers, swamps, ancient ruins, and dense foliage of many kinds. The lighting and water effects are very impressive. At the same time, Eden's beauty is tempered by its dangers. Fatigue, sickness, and the terror of being stalked are conveyed in an organic and immersive fashion, which makes them all the scarier.Miasmata is a beautiful sandbox experience. I also found it very frightening, at times. Perhaps not everyone will find it as scary as I did, but anyone who loves exploring will find it very engaging."
